<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910329-0012</DOCNO><DOCID>910329-0012.</DOCID><HL>   Forstmann Little Set   To Offer Five Million   More of Topps Shares</HL><DATE>03/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   TOPP</CO><IN>RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)DIVIDENDS (DIV)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- The owner of Topps Co., the bubble gum andbaseball card maker, proposed to sell five million more ofits shares, which at current prices would generate more than$80 million.   The proposed sale would be the third time that ForstmannLittle andamp; Co. has profited handsomely from its Toppsinvestment. The closely held investment concern took theBrooklyn-based company private in 1984 in a $96 millionleveraged buyout.</LP><TEXT>   In 1987, Forstmann made a public offering of 30% of Topps'shares, and sold 1.3 million of its own shares at $13 each,generating about $17 million. Later that year, afterabandoning a secondary offering, Forstmann received about $96million when Topps declared a special dividend of $10 ashare.   Even after selling five million shares in the offeringfiled with the Securities and Exchange Commission,Forstmann-related partnerships still will hold about 20million shares, or about 40% of the company, valued at about$335 million at current prices. No shares are being offeredby management and the company won't receive any proceeds fromthe offering.   The secondary offering will be managed by Alex. Brown andamp;Sons and Bear, Stearns andamp; Co.   Separately, Topps increased its quarterly dividend 20% tosix cents a share from five cents, payable May 1 to stock ofrecord April 17. Shares in the secondary offering won'treceive the dividend payable May 1.   In its fourth quarter ended March 2, Topps reported netincome of $13.8 million, or 29 cents a share, compared with$10.5 million, or 22 cents a share, the year earlier. Salesrose to $67.5 million from $67.3 million.   Topps' sales rose 18% in fiscal 1991 to $290 million aftera 24% rise in fiscal 1990.</TEXT></DOC>